{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503516"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:02:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:02:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2037"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.03,0.15,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65819"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2037"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3341"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42440"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65819"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by his wife with a 24-hour history of deterioration in his mental state and associated agitation. His wife reports he has a medical history of atrial fibrillation, depression, epilepsy, insomnia, and chronic back pain, for which he has recently been started on tramadol. His regular medications include amiodarone, apixaban, phenytoin, and temazepam. His wife reports that he has been trying an over-the-counter medication to help with his mood but is unsure what this is. He is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol socially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears agitated. His pulse rate is 104/min, blood pressure 160/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. He is warm and flushed. Neurological examination shows rigidity with hyperreflexia and dilated pupils bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following substances may be responsible for his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["St. John\u0027s Wort","Alcohol","Haloperidol","Amiodarone","Phenytoin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the clinical features of serotonin syndrome, a potentially life-threatening condition caused by excessive serotonergic activity in the central and peripheral nervous systems. The combination of mental state changes, autonomic hyperactivity (tachycardia, hypertension, hyperthermia), and neuromuscular abnormalities (rigidity, hyperreflexia) is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESt. John\u0027s Wort\u003C/strong\u003E is the likely culprit as it has significant serotonergic activity and can interact with tramadol to precipitate serotonin syndrome. This herbal supplement is commonly available over-the-counter and is often perceived as \u0027natural\u0027 and therefore safe by patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol\u003C/strong\u003E withdrawal can cause autonomic hyperactivity and agitation, but this patient\u0027s social drinking pattern and timing of last drink make this unlikely. Additionally, alcohol withdrawal would not typically cause hyperreflexia and rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E can cause neuroleptic malignant syndrome, which can appear similar to serotonin syndrome. However, this medication is not listed in the patient\u0027s history, and the rapid onset would be unusual for neuroleptic malignant syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E has numerous side effects including thyroid dysfunction, but would not cause this acute presentation with features of serotonin syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E toxicity typically presents with ataxia, nystagmus, and drowsiness rather than the features described. Additionally, this is a long-term medication for the patient without recent changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of serotonin syndrome includes immediate discontinuation of all serotonergic agents and supportive care. Severe cases are treated with cyproheptadine, a serotonin antagonist. The condition can progress to multi-organ failure if not recognised and treated promptly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Serotonin syndrome is characterised by neuromuscular changes, autonomic hyperactivity, and mental state changes","St. John\u0027s Wort can interact with tramadol to cause serotonin syndrome","Diagnosis of serotonin syndrome is clinical and treatment includes cyproheptadine"],"references":["Scotton WJ, Hill LJ, Williams AC, Barnes NM. Serotonin Syndrome: Pathophysiology, Clinical Features, Management, and Potential Future Directions. Int J Tryptophan Res. 2019;12:1178646919873925-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2037"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T08:51:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T08:52:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":